The paper deals with sequential hypothesis testing, which is a problem in both machine learning and algorithms. The paper introduces a new condition, split-neighborly, which is weaker than the previously known condition, k-neighborly. This suggests that the paper could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.DS (data structures and algorithms), cs.AI (artificial intelligence), and cs.LG (machine learning). Additionally, the paper involves analyzing the query cost of algorithms, which could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.CC (computational complexity) and cs.IT (information theory).
